<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEBATE OVER FAIRNESS OF PROP. 13 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jonathan Coupal's column, like Proposition 13 itself, is simple, easy to 
understand, and wrong ("Proposition 13 Has Made Everyone's Tax Reasonable," 
Op-Ed Page, Aug. 29). It is also equivocal. 
</P>
<P>
Property tax laws should not contain "absolute certain(ies)" any more than the 
price of food or fuel should or could be absolutely certain. 
</P>
<P>
Plainly, it is not good social policy to throw people from their homes for 
non-payment of exorbitant taxes; but it is also poor policy to lock in 
assessment increases with no consideration of future budget requirements. 
</P>
<P>
Justice Frank Richardson's "roughly comparable" analogy to sales taxes refutes 
Coupal's point. Sales taxes are directly related to current value. As the cost 
of goods fluctuates, so does the cost of government, and so do sales tax 
collections; to imply that one class of Californian (long-term property owners) 
should be immune to inflation at the expense of others, is not "equal 
protection under the law." 
</P>
<P>
Coupal's argument that everyone's tax is "reasonable" because of an arbitrary 
1% cap ignores the point. If our schools, our hospitals, our fire and police 
are responsive to us all, then we must all pay a fair share. The 1% tax 
currently provides sufficient funds. 
</P>
<P>
But what if housing prices had not so outrageously surpassed inflation to 
provide those funds? Are we to devise a new plan, some new Proposition 13, when 
the real estate rocket levels off? Is that "reasonable"? 
</P>
<P>
Proposition 13 is a Ponzi scheme, where the new entrants pay the bills of the 
older players. It is "unfair." It is shortsighted. It is not good tax policy. 
</P>
<P>
JOSEPH W. DOHERTY 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
