<HEADLINE>
<P>
'FINE-TUNING' THE MEDICARE SURTAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's not enough to "fine-tune" the Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act, as The 
Times suggested in its editorial defending this law ("All It Needs Is 
Fine-Tuning," Sept. 11). This new program needs a major overhaul. 
</P>
<P>
As a member of Congress who voted against this bill, I have argued from the 
time its passage was imminent that we should scrap it and start over. Our 
original goal was right: to protect older Americans from the financial 
devastation that a major, long-term illness can cause. But we never achieved 
that goal. Instead of providing help with long-term nursing home or home health 
care -- the costs of which are feared the most by the elderly -- Congress 
provided a number of less essential benefits. It was no surprise that 
beneficiaries objected to paying very substantial fees for them. 
</P>
<P>
The only truly catastrophic benefit of this new law is the unlimited 
hospitalization. The other principal new benefits are help with physicians' 
fees and prescription drug expenses. Large bills in both cases can cause 
hardship, but rarely are the costs "catastrophic," $2,000 worth of doctors' or 
pharmaceutical bills in a year is a modest expense compared to $30,000 for a 
yearlong stay in a typical nursing home, which really is catastrophic for all 
but the most affluent elderly. 
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, many of the elderly have private insurance to pay for the 
hospital, physician, and prescription drug expenses that Medicare does not 
cover, but virtually none have insurance for long-term nursing home and home 
health care. 
</P>
<P>
The existence of this new Medicare program has made it all but impossible for 
Congress to address the need for help with the costs of long-term care. Because 
of the huge expenses involved in nursing home or home health care, Congress 
cannot create a federal program to pay for them without asking beneficiaries to 
bear part of the cost. But we will also be hard-pressed to ask recipients to 
pay even higher health care fees after imposing such large premium increases 
and a surtax on the elderly to pay for some of these other, less urgent 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
Congress will soon be deciding whether to repeal or merely adjust the financing 
of this new law -- possibly in a way that would be detrimental to low- and 
middle-income elderly. Repeal is the right course: If we go back to square one 
and provide, instead, long-term care benefits -- the true "catastrophic" 
benefits that the elderly need and want the most (and probably thought they 
were getting with this bill) -- we're certain to see a much greater willingness 
on their part to help pay for them. 
</P>
<P>
REP. ANTHONY C. BEILENSON 
</P>
<P>
D-Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
