</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
AND BRUINS NEEDED MORE OF EVERYTHING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bruin heaven '89 lasted less than a week, from about Jeff George's last pass to 
the end of the third quarter of that 6-24 Tennessee nightmare on Linda Vista. 
</P>
<P>
Unless the opener was a complete aberration, the Bruins are in a lot more 
trouble than the Trojans, who were basically beaten because of a fluke tipped 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
UCLA was run over, flattened, humiliated, and not by Oklahoma or Nebraska, but 
by what is very probably a middling SEC team with not much of a passer. How 
could it happen? 
</P>
<P>
My suspicion is that Terry Donahue used a straight-up defensive approach, and 
when Bret Johnson and the offense started having trouble with the Vols' 
defensive pressure, the game was gone. 
</P>
<P>
In other words, the Bruins asked for it. This might have been one of those rare 
times Terry didn't worry enough. 
</P>
<P>
CHARLES CHICCOA, Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
