<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: BURNED VIETNAMESE DELAYS VISIT TO U.S. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Vietnamese woman whose naked, screaming image as a child in 1972 became one 
of the enduring symbols of the Vietnam War has indefinitely postponed her trip 
to the United States, an American sponsor said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Phan Thi Kim Phuc, 26, decided to cancel the trip she had planned this month 
primarily because of health reasons, said Merle Ratner, her spokeswoman in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
The shocking black-and-white photograph of 9-year-old Kim, screaming in pain 
and horror as she ran naked down a road after a South Vietnamese air raid, 
received a Pulitzer Prize. 
</P>
<P>
What is not shown in the photo, said Los Angeles-based Associated Press 
Photographer Nick Ut, who took the picture and was instrumental in saving Kim's 
life, is that her body was "like barbecue." Kim, who had received permission 
from Vietnam to tour the United State, still suffers physical problems from the 
burns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
