<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRASH PROMPTS BUENA PARK MAYOR TO CALL FOR STRICTER CONTROLS ON FULLERTON 
FLIGHTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBORAH CARPENTIER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Buena Park Mayor Donna L. Chessen on Friday called for stricter controls 
regulating flights from Fullerton Municipal Airport, saying a rash of plane 
crashes has left residents living in "a nightmare" of fear. 
</P>
<P>
"We are continuing to become more populated, and our residents don't deserve 
this," Chessen said. "It comes close to being an earthquake, but it is actually 
worse in one respect. You can't prepare for it. It's a nightmare." 
</P>
<P>
Joined at a press conference by City Councilwoman Rhonda J. McCune, Chessen 
expressed concern over a series of accidents involving small airplanes flying 
in and out of the Fullerton airport. 
</P>
<P>
The latest accident came Wednesday shortly before 4:30 p.m. when a two-seat 
Cessna 152, carrying an instructor and a student pilot, lost power about a 
minute after takeoff and crashed at the intersection of Artesia Boulevard and 
Darlington Street in Buena Park. 
</P>
<P>
The student pilot, Moyra Pimm, 29, of Great Britain, remained in critical but 
stable condition Friday at UCI Medical Center with burns over 50% of her body. 
The instructor, Bradley Pearce, 28, of Garden Grove, was treated for burns on 
his arm and released. 
</P>
<P>
The accident is being investigated by the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
"This is the third plane crash to occur in Buena Park since December, and the 
11th since 1966," Chessen said. "And because of the flight pattern, it is more 
likely that a crash will occur in our city than in Fullerton." 
</P>
<P>
While stopping short of calling for the Fullerton airport to be closed, Chessen 
nevertheless expressed outrage over the number of accidents and called on 
Fullerton officials to work with the Federal Aviation Administration to review 
airport procedures to make sure everything is being done to prevent more 
accidents from happening. 
</P>
<P>
Chessen said she had directed the city staff to research and inquire into the 
FAA's methods and policies to find a way the agency can better regulate flights 
at the Fullerton airport. 
</P>
<P>
"While Buena Park realizes dealing with a huge federal entity such as the FAA 
is no small task, we believe it is our responsibility to the residents and 
businesses in Buena Park to do all we can to ensure their safety." 
</P>
<P>
As an example of what can be done, Chessen noted that the city of San Diego 
prohibits evening "touch and go" landing practices, the standard learning 
technique used most frequently by student pilots. 
</P>
<P>
She noted that occupants of the last two plane crashes in Buena Park were 
students and teachers. 
</P>
<P>
Joining a chorus of other Buena Park officials, Councilwoman McCune called on 
the Fullerton Municipal Airport to be closed. 
</P>
<P>
"Fullerton's City Council does not care about us," McCune said. "They have not 
done one thing to show any concern. I want to see Fullerton airport closed 
down, but at the very minimum, they should at least change the flight pattern." 
</P>
<P>
McCune said the city would like the FAA to impose stricter regulations 
regarding touch-and-go landings and look into the possibility of prohibiting 
student pilots from using the airport. She also complained that planes 
continually fly too low in approaching and leaving the airport. 
</P>
<P>
"Maybe we are reaching a day when stronger controls should be made in regard to 
pleasure flying," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Chessen noted that some critics had proposed that Buena Park change its zoning 
laws "and move people out from under the flight pattern of the airport." She 
called that "an impossible option with thousands of people, homes and 
businesses located adjacent to the airport." 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton officials said earlier they were satisfied with the facility's 
operation, with City Manager William C. Winter describing the airport as "a 
very safe place. The record of incidents does not reflect an alarming 
situation." 
</P>
<P>
Sylvia Paoli, chairwoman of Fullerton's Airport Users Task Force and a pilot 
for two decades, called the reaction by Buena Park officials unwarranted. 
</P>
<P>
"I wish people would try to step out of themselves a little bit and realize the 
airport is not unleashing an atom bomb on Buena Park," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
